 account of a central, yet overlooked, woman writer who served as a model and a contributor within a major cultural tradition. For those working in Victorian studies or comparative fascism and for those interested in Nietzsche and his influence on European intellectuals, Kobylians’ka emerges in this study as an unlikely, but no less active, trailblazer in the social and aesthetic theories that would define European debates about culture, science, and politics in the first half of the twentieth century. For those interested in questions of transnationalism and intersectionality, this study’s discussion of Kobylians’ka’s hybrid cultural identity and philosophical program exemplifies cultural interchange and irreducible complexities of cultural identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Eastern (see also Russian & Former Soviet Union).2bisacsh  aComparative Fascism.  aEuropean Intellectualism.  aFeminism.  aModernist Literature.  aNationalism.  aNietzsche.  aNietzscheanism.  aOl’ha Kobylians’ka.  aUkrainian Literature.  aVictorian.  aWomen’s Writing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Pilot 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144263076540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442630765423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442630765.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  UT